Talking points this version unlocks in interview

DTO separation → "prevents over-posting, decouples API contract from schema"
Service layer + interface → "controller stays thin, business logic is testable in isolation, DI via IEmployeeService"
Transaction wrapping on create → straight from your CashBankEntryService pattern — you can genuinely say "I use this in production for double-entry accounting flows"
AutoMapper → common follow-up: "why not just map manually?" — answer: reduces boilerplate, but you'd avoid it for complex nested mappings where explicit control matters more
Global exception middleware → "single place to log and shape error responses, no scattered try/catch in every controller"
Signals over BehaviorSubject/manual subscribe → this is your strongest card — you can speak to it from actual FinVentory work, not just theory
Pagination → "raw ToListAsync() doesn't scale past a few hundred rows"
